metadata.name: Ascii Timescapes #3
metadata.description:
This token takes Ascii Landscapes and adds a time element. Each token randomly generates scene components like Mountains, Hills, Fields, Far Fields, Pond, River, Birds, Clouds and a House. Then the code grabs your system clock and generates the sky based on the time. Because the Sun/Moon or symmetrical, the code does it's best to give a decent sky. The day starts early.

Number of each scene component is based on the fxhash variable so the combinations are very large. I wanted to take my previous ascii landscapes and give everyone a chance to see their scene change throughout the day.

Click/tap the image to cycle through color, dithered and black/white versions of the scene. Finally press 's' to save the image as a png.

metadata.name: Polyphemus in Four Moods #5
metadata.description:
In Greek mythology Polyphemus was a one-eyed giant, a Cyclops, the son of Poseidon and Thoosa. In the Odyssey, he battles Odysseus and is blinded by the hero.

"Then from out the cave the mighty Polyphemus answered them: 'My friends, it is Noman that is slaying me by guile and not by force.' "
    ~ Homer's Odyssey, Book 9

Yes, Polyphemus was a monster - a man eating, one-eyed giant - but was there more to his story? Odysseus and his men did trespass and eat his food. They went on their adventure looking for "monsters" to kill, and they found them.  But "monster"?  If you mess with a snake and it bites you, you don't blame the snake do you? 

Maybe there's more to these characters. Like us, maybe they have (or had) lives and just want to be left alone. 


--- 

Three variations:

- No inner frame
- Inner frame
- Inner frame with artist's signature (rare)

metadata.name: menToll #78
metadata.description:
menToll was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Toll (from the Permutations Series). (c. 1965) Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the fifth in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

menToll is two layered piece. A 2x2 array of arrays of circles contained within a background square. A similar sized array of squares (with no background of its own) is superimposed and centered on top. Each array of circles with a square has an opacity gradient applied to it allowing its uniquely colored random background to show through its elements. The superimposed top layer of squares is a solid random color.

There are many Gestalt interactions within this piece. Circle groups within each of their containers interact with each other, and their background, in interesting ways. Each new generation with its random color assignments significantly affects your depth perception. The top layer appears to come forward or recede depending on the layer it overlaps. And depending on color combinations there is a variety of "after-imagism" interactions between the squares in the top set. More candy for your mind.

Dr. Bill Generative Art OG @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Tesseract #119
metadata.description:
'Tesseract' is a generative collection drawing on the concept of the cube from oneirology, the interpretation of dreams. In many mythologies and fields of study, the square is considered a 'perfect shape', thus with its abstraction into three isometric dimensions, the cube is seen by some as a representation of the various aspects of the human condition.

In 'Tesseract', the ribbons flowing between the cubes represent the shared experiences that connect us all. No matter how different our lives might be, we all go through the same joys, sorrows, trials, tribulations and experience attachments of varying degrees. 

It is these experiences that bind us together and make us who we are. With these concepts in mind, viewers are invited to interpret each composition as it relates to them and their unique story, from the perspective of that which has been and that which is yet to be experienced.

Press 'S' to save a high resolution PNG at 2400 x 3396 px.

metadata.name: Reading a book #485
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: Efflorescence #213
metadata.description:
Efflorescence is a piece that bridges between Pouya and Fatima's hand crafted tiles and Gorilla Sun's generative work, and reflects their collective love for patterns and colour. Efflorescence is a generative token that creates unique compositions by random arrangement of different tiles and the colorisation thereof.

This generative token would not have been possible without Zeno Zeng's SVG runtime for P5JS!

Press the down arrow button to export an SVG of the artwork. In live view stroke width can be adjusted by zooming in and out.

metadata.name: Over the hills... #102
metadata.description:
A flurry of shapes, waves and colors at the intersection of figurative and abstract.

Created with p5js using multiple shape primitives, gradient noise and various sine & cosine functions.

The algorithm contains multiple loops plotting several thousands of shapes and lines and may take up to 12 seconds to display the artwork.

Dutch action 10-8-6-4 at 10 minute intervals.
